                </li>
                <li>
                  <details>
                    <summary>
                      improve real-time encoding performance
                    </summary>
                    <ol>
                      <li>
                        <a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/ffmpeg/comments/aj42ci/is_there_anything_i_can_do_to_improve_realtime/">improve real-time encoding performance</a>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <p>Switch the order of your commands so that the video processing filters come after your input.<br></p>
                        <pre class="hljs-code">ffmpeg -i "%userprofile%\Desktop\1.ts" -hide_banner -report -f "v4l2" -vf   "fps=fps=30.000,scale=-2:720:flags=fast_bilinear,format=yuv420p" -vstats   -r "30.000" -c:v "libx264" -crf "23" -an -dn -sn -map_metadata "-1" -preset "faster" -f "matroska" output.mkv</pre>
                        <p>First you have to find out whether your hardware is maxing out because of the "capture and decode" vs the "encode".</p>
                        <p>Use the fps filter to drop the number of frames you are trying to process at the start of the filter chain using both fps filter and -r command. You can always revert to 60fps if you find that this is not the limiting factor. You may also find that decimate may be less intensive than fps, but fps is a more elegant method of primary frame rate conversion. I suspect that you will not want to drop the frame rate, but at least try it to see whether it helps reduce the amount of frames you are trying to encode.</p>
                        <p>Drop the resolution to 1280x720 using the scale filter. See if it makes a difference? If it makes no difference, bring it back to 1920x1080. Try fast bilinear scaling, which gets you about 10% extra over the default scaling. There is also cuda scaling.</p>
                        <p>Iconoclast personal opinion: 1080p60 + ultrafast may sound like it is going to give you the best visual quality, but if the system is struggling to keep up, 720p30 + faster/fast/medium preset may give you a better final quality. Ultrafast is not always visually appealing and can be blocky with washed out colors. Well-encoded 720p is sometimes better than badly-encoded 1080p. It all depends on the screensize and distance that you are viewing from.</p>Of course, you can try going down the hardware decode, hardware scale and hardware encode route. YMMV. <a href="https://trac.ffmpeg.org/wiki/HWAccelIntro" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow ugc" target="_blank">https://trac.ffmpeg.org/wiki/HWAccelIntro</a>. The benefit is massively dependent on your hardware. On my laptop, it hardly makes much difference compared to good old x264.
                        <pre class="hljs-code">ffmpeg -hide_banner -hwaccels will help you work out what hardware accelerations are available.</pre>
                        <p>Leave -threads alone while you are trying to find out where your bottlenecks are. Add back if you are trying to restrict FFmpeg, otherwise the default of -threads "0" seems to optimize itself out just fine.</p>
                        <p>Play with the following, tweaking the frame rate, resolution and preset.</p>
                        <pre class="hljs-code">ffmpeg -i "%userprofile%\Desktop\1.ts" -hide_banner -report -f "v4l2" -vf   "fps=fps=30.000,scale=-2:720:flags=fast_bilinear,format=yuv420p" -vstats   -r "30.000" -c:v "libx264" -crf "23" -an -dn -sn -map_metadata "-1" -preset "faster" -f "matroska" output.mkv</pre>
                        <p>Also, try dumping your raw stream to null to measure the effect on CPU of just the input/decode chain.</p>
                        <pre class="hljs-code">ffmpeg -i TestVideo.ts -hide_banner -report -f "v4l2" -c:v "wrapped_avframe" -an -dn -sn -map_metadata "-1" -f "null" /dev/null</pre>
                      </li>
