          <li><details><summary>How to process video
              </summary>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p><a href="https://forum.videohelp.com/threads/300421-Split-Files-By-Size-Seamlessly-Possible">How to process video</a>:With most highly compressed formats like Divx you have to make your splits on a keyframe (I frame). Anywhere else will cause problems. Formats like Divx/XviD have keyframes about every 300 frames by default. That's one way they get high compression. A keyframe is a complete frame and the ones following and proceeding are just partial frames. If you split anywhere else, you would have to re-encode that portion to preserve audio/video sync. In avidemux, you navigate by keyframes using the "&lt;&lt;" and "&gt;&gt;". In vdub , it the arrows "&lt;" "&gt;" with the key picture underneath. If neither of these work there is likely something wrong with your video. I say this because you shouldn't have to cut on keyframes with avidemux when using XviD/DivX because it automatically asks you if you want to enable "smart copy" which will render around the cut site if the cut is not on a keyframe.</p>
                  <p><a href="https://superuser.com/a/536493/1003800">BEGIN How to split files by size:</a></p>
                  <pre class="page"><code>"%ProgramFiles%\MKVToolNix\mkvmerge.exe" --split 2G --compression 0:none --compression 1:none --clusters-in-meta-seek -o "2.mkv" "1.mkv"</code></pre>This command will split the file into segments 2-001.mkv, 2-002.mkv, etc. In general, if the file plays on your computer but does NOT play on tv or disc player (bluray, dvd), your problem will usually be header compression.
